1. 
if err != nil in Go
//The if err != nil literally means "err is not equal to nil"
It tests whether an error occurred by comparing the error variable to nil. 
In Go, when an operation succeeds, the error return value is nil (equivalent to null in other languages).
When something goes wrong, the error contains details about what failed.

2. log.fatal(err) //shutdown and log the error message. Fatal is a function from Go's log package that terminates your program immediately after logging a message. 

3. != means not equal to
defer ln.close() //defer means at the end of the function close the port. so here it means after logging close the port

